 Convergence
\series default
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Let
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{m}=\bigcup_{k=0}^{3^{m-1}-1}\left(\frac{3k+1}{3^{m}},\frac{3k+2}{3^{m}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge1$
\end_inset

 set 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}=\left[0,1\right]\backslash\bigcup_{m=1}^{n}A_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\lim_{n\to\infty}C_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the random variable defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{n}\left(\omega\right)=\omega+I_{C_{n}}\left(\omega\right)
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the random variable defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(\omega\right)=\omega$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Claim: 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 converges almost surely to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(\lim_{n\to\infty}X_{n}=X\right)=1
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Proof: 
\series default
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{m}$
\end_inset

 are not disjoint we cannot compute the measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 easily.
 We reason intuitively that each successive 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{m}$
\end_inset

 removes from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 an additional 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{m-1}$
\end_inset

 intervals of length 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{m}$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(\left[0,1\right]\backslash C\right) & = & \sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\frac{2^{m-1}}{3^{m}}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{m}=\frac{1}{2}\left(2\right)=1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(C\right)$
\end_inset

 must be 0.
 By definition of the indicator 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}\neq X$
\end_inset

 only on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(C\right)$
\end_inset

 being 0 is tantamount to the set on which 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}\neq X$
\end_inset

 for infinitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 having measure 0.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(\lim_{n\to\infty}X_{n}\neq X\right)=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


