\series bold
Proof: 
\series default
Express all the numbers in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 in their ternary representation.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Removing middle thirds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from each successive 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to removing all numbers which have a digit of 1 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th place after the decimal, in their ternary expansion.
 Therefore the only numbers remaining in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 are those which admit a ternary representation consisting solely of 0s
 and 2s (terminating decimals, which have 2 ternary representations, are
 not a contradiction).
 The mapping 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

replace all 2s with 1s
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 onto the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Note the mapping is not into since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{7}{9}=.20222\dots_{3}\rightarrow0.10111\dots_{2}=0.11_{2}\leftarrow.220000\dots=\frac{8}{9}
\]

\end_inset

but by Cantor-Berstein we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[0,1\right]\right|\leq\left|C\right|\leq\left|\left[0,1\right]\right|$
\end_inset

 and the claims follows .
